{"rawJson":null,"m_plot":"Sheldon Bart (Fred Ward) is a drifter, and a small-time con man. He meets his old friend, Brother Bud (Harry Dean Stanton), a big-time con man into faith healing and fencing stolen cars, at his revival tent outside a small town. While he's helping Brother Bud, he falls in love with Arlene (Cindy Williams), a local supermarket clerk who believes in UFOs and is deeply religious and deeply lonely. When Arlene has a vision of a coming UFO, everyone deals with it in their own way.","m_cast":null,"m_reception":"The film received mostly positive reviews. Roger Ebert gave the film a 4 star review, calling the film a \"great and goofy comedy\", concluding with \"Like \"Repo Man,\" \"Turtle Diary\" and \"Hannah and Her Sisters,\" it is willing to go for originality in a world that prizes the entertainment assembly line.\"[4] | Vincent Canby, a reviewer writing for the New York Times, said that the film has a \"raffish tone\" and is \"exuberantly nutty,\" while also praising the casting.[5] Kevin Thomas, writing for the Los Angeles Times concluded his review with, \"Williams manages to be adorable and never seems all-out crazy; like Ward, you do believe in her, whether or not you believe in UFOs.\"[6]","m_production":null,"m_sequel":null,"m_based_on":null,"m_directed_by":"John Binder","m_produced_by":"Melvin Simon","m_screenplay_by":null,"m_story_by":null,"m_starring":"Fred Ward Cindy Williams Harry Dean Stanton","m_music_by":null,"m_cinematography":null,"m_edited_by":null,"m_production_company":null,"m_distributed_by":"Universal Pictures Paramount CIC","m_release_dates":"1985 (1985) |  |  |  | ","m_running_time":"93 minutes","m_country":null,"m_language":"English | UFOria is a science fiction/comedy movie starring Fred Ward, Harry Dean Stanton, Harry Carey, Jr. and Cindy Williams. It was directed and written by John Binder. The film includes small appearances by Peggy McKay, Joe Unger, Hank Worden and Charlotte Stewart. Filming was completed in 1981, but the film was not theatrically released until 1985. Due to poor audience attendance, the film was not a financial success. It was only released on VHS in 1987 by MCA Home Video, now known as Universal Studios Home Entertainment. |  | ","m_budget":null,"m_box_office":null,"m_marketing":null,"m_reference":"^ \"Uforia\". TV Guide. Retrieved May 17, 2014.  | ^ \"Uforia\". WorldCat. Retrieved May 17, 2014.  | ^ Armstrong, Collin (January 5, 2007). \"Seldom Seen review - Uforia\". Twitch Film. Retrieved May 17, 2014.  | ^ Ebert, Roger (April 25, 1986). \"Uforia\". Roger Ebert.com. Retrieved May 17, 2014.  | ^ Canby, Vincent (January 3, 1986). \"The Screen:: 'Uforia,' A Comedy, Finally Arrives\". New York Times. Retrieved May 17, 2014.  | ^ Thomas, Kevin (July 2, 1985). \"Movie Review : A Close Encounter With 'Uforia'\". Los Angeles Times. Retrieved May 17, 2014. ","m_external_link":"UFOria at the Internet Movie Database | ","m_poster":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/58/UFOria_cover.jpg/220px-UFOria_cover.jpg","m_production_companies":null,"m_written_by":"John Binder"}